    "summary": "Dr Ayo Adene, M.B;B.S (Ib), MPH (Ib), Dip Health Sys (Netherlands), is a medical doctor with more than 20 years\u2019 experience solving challenges in HIV & AIDS, Malaria, Tuberculosis, Ebola, Polio, leading Nutrition & Maternal, Neonatal & Child Health (MNCH) programs, and leading health financing programs.\n\nDr Adene\u2019s core competencies were recognized early-on, in 2006, when he led development of a detailed US$ 50 million budget & work plan for the World Bank Multi-country Assistance Project (MAP2) grant to Nigeria\u2019s Ministry of Health. As a result, he became a pioneer in the US$7.8 Billion costing process to develop Nigeria\u2019s 5-year National Strategic Framework (NSF) 2005-2009 for HIV. \n\nSince then, Dr Adene has been Team Leader for Rwanda\u2019s first Integrated Child Policy in 2009, leading a nationwide survey of Health, Education & Justice for Orphans and Vulnerable Children who are survivors of genocide, including Internally Displaced Children (IDPs) in UNHCR-managed camps all over Rwanda. Dr Adene led the first nationwide survey on Maternal, Neonatal & Child Health in independent South Sudan in 2010. In 2013, Dr Adene was also Team Leader for another nationwide Maternal, Neonatal & Child Health survey in Suriname. \n\nIn 2015, Dr Adene was Senior Program Manager for Fundraising, Advocacy & Program Development, in a 4-country health financing public private partnership between the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in the Netherlands, Pharmaccess Foundation, Philips, Vodafone, Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, and Kenya, Tanzania, Ghana & Nigeria. In 2016, Ayo\u2019s outstanding business development was recognized by the Paris-based Organization for Economic Cooperation & Development (OECD), and shortlisted for the Development Assistance Prize for Taking Innovation to Scale. And in 2021, he was shortlisted for the Aspen New Voices Fellowship.\n\nAyo Adene is also a skilled biographer, essayist & poet, who has worked in 4 continents and 15 countries, and is resident in the Netherlands.\n",
